The paper discusses the performance of spatial multiplexing systems in the presence of interference, which is a common problem in wireless communication networks. This topic falls under the Information Theory (cs.IT) and Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of opportunistic scheduling and interference alignment techniques, which are relevant to the Signal Processing (cs.SI) and Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-categories. Finally, the paper discusses the use of real and complex encoding for multi-user spatial multiplexing, which is relevant to the Computer Engineering (cs.CE) sub-category.
